Among the \Sexpr{dim(cukeAlg)[1]} individuals sequenced, we identified
\Sexpr{nSppAll} species. All orders of sea cucumbers were represented. The order
Aspidochirotida, and in particular the family Holothuriidae were the most
exhaustively sampled (\Sexpr{formatC(100*nSppAsp/nSppAll, width=2, format="d")}
and \Sexpr{formatC(100*nSppHol/nSppAll, width=2, format="d")} of the total number
of individuals respectively), with all genera and subgenera of the Holothuriidae
represented, and 65\% for the currently accepted species names.

On the entire dataset, regardless of the method or the distance threshold used,
the number of estimated ESUs was greater than the number of named species
suggesting cryptic diversity . The pairwise distance method led to lower
estimates than the clustering method and was less sensitive to the type of
distance used (Fig.~\ref{fig:groups-comparison-plot}). At the order level, and
for the Holothuriidae, the estimated number of ESUs plateaued for thresholds >
4\% with the clustering method and for thresholds > 2\% with the pairwise
distance method.

When all sequences where analyzed, the proportion of singletons varied between
35\% and 40\% for distance thresholds > 2\% for the pairwise method and for
thresholds > 4\% for the clustering method
(Fig.~\ref{fig:groups-comparison-plot}). Typically, these thresholds were more
variable when analyzing each orders individually (3\% and 5\% for both the
Aspidochirotida and the Holothuriidae, 3\% and 2.5\% for the Apodida, 3\% and
3\% for the Dendrochirotida, 2\% and 4\% for the Elasipodida.)

For the rest of the study we use the ESUs as delineated by the clustering method
with a threshold of 4\% based on the raw distances. This threshold provided a
compromise by separating ESUs with different color patterns or ecology, without
splitting ESUs that showed some level of geographic structure across their
range. This distance threshold also corresponds to the level where all methods
tested provided similar estimates of the proportion of singletons. We also
favored this approach as it led to reciprocally monophyletic groups that
facilitated the investigation of geographic patterns of diversity and
diversification.

With this threshold, the number of estimated ESUs is
\Sexpr{length(load_species_clusterGrps("raw", "all", 0.02))}. The difference
with the number of named species comes from species complexes. These complexes
can be deeply divergent populations across the range of species previously
thought to be circum-tropical. For instance, \textit{Holothuria arenicola} forms
a complex with different ESUs in the Caribbean basin, the Eastern Pacific and
the rest of the Indo-Pacific. For this species and others (e.g.,
\textit{Holothuria hilla}), these divergent lineages have overlapping ranges,
which made their recognition as distinct evolutionary units
challenging. Additionally, many species thought to occur in both Indian and
Pacific Oceans (e.g., \textit{Holothuria pervicax}, \textit{Holothuria
  fuscocinerea}), or to reach peripheral areas of the Indo-Pacific (e.g.,
\textit{Holothuria cinerascens} has ESUs both in Hawaii and the Red Sea), appear
highly divergent genetically, sometimes accompanied with morphological
differences.

Our large scale sampling effort also led to the discovery of ESUs that appear to
be undescribed species. These include large, commercially important species. For
the Holothuriidae that have been the most comprehensively sampled, 12 ESUs
clearly differentiated morphologically, are potentially new species not directly
part of a species complex.

For some groups that were sampled extensively, we recovered less ESUs than there
are described species. Notably, in \textit{Opheodesoma}, that currently include
11 species, we only recovered 4 ESUs as well as 2 probably undescribed species.

In a few cases, groups of individuals that appear morphologically differentiated
were grouped together in an ESU. This was in particular the case of
\textit{Holothuria edulis} which harbors two color morphs: gray  and fuschia;
and several species in \textit{Stichopus}. One the other hand, there were some
cases of species that were split into several ESUs but that did not seem to be
differentiated morphologically and that had broadly overlapping ranges.


